To find the minimum value of a quadratic form, we can use the method of completing the square.

First, we rewrite the quadratic form in matrix notation:

\[
\begin{pmatrix} x & y & z \end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix} 3 & -2 & -3 \\ -2 & 12 & -6 \\ -3 & -6 & 27 \end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix} x \\ y \\ z \end{pmatrix}
+ \begin{pmatrix} 0 & -4 & -6 \end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix} x \\ y \\ z \end{pmatrix}
+ \begin{pmatrix} -8 \\ -12 \end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix} y \\ z \end{pmatrix}
\]

We then diagonalize the matrix:

\[
\begin{pmatrix} 3 & -2 & -3 \\ -2 & 12 & -6 \\ -3 & -6 & 27 \end{pmatrix}
= PDP^{-1}
\]

where $D$ is a diagonal matrix containing the eigenvalues of the original matrix, and $P$ is an invertible matrix whose columns are the eigenvectors.

Once we have the diagonalized form, we can rewrite the quadratic form as:

\[
\begin{pmatrix} x & y & z \end{pmatrix}
PDP^{-1}
\begin{pmatrix} x \\ y \\ z \end{pmatrix}
+ \begin{pmatrix} 0 & -4 & -6 \end{pmatrix}
P^{-1}
\begin{pmatrix} x \\ y \\ z \end{pmatrix}
+ \begin{pmatrix} -8 \\ -12 \end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix} y \\ z \end{pmatrix}
\]

We can then complete the square for each term involving the diagonal matrix $D$.

Finally, we substitute back the original variables $x,$ $y,$ and $z$ to obtain the minimum value of the quadratic form.

This process can be quite tedious, but it is a systematic way to find the minimum value of a quadratic form.

